>
  <p>Not every rash or spot requires a doctor's visit, but some symptoms should never be ignored. This guide helps you determine when to seek medical attention.</p>

  <h2>Warning Signs Requiring Immediate Medical Attention</h2>
  <p>Seek emergency care for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Signs of infection:</strong> Increasing redness, swelling, warmth, pus, or fever.</li>
    <li><strong>Rapid spreading:</strong> A rash or redness that grows quickly.</li>
    <li><strong>Breathing difficulty:</strong> Shortness of breath, wheezing, or throat swelling (may indicate severe allergic reaction).</li>
    <li><strong>Widespread blistering:</strong> Especially if accompanied by fever or pain.</li>
    <li><strong>Severe pain:</strong> Skin that is extremely painful to touch.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to See a General Practitioner</h2>
  <p>Make an appointment with your GP if:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A skin rash persists longer than two weeks without improvement.</li>
    <li>Itching or skin irritation disrupts daily life or sleep.</li>
    <li>A mole changes in shape, color, or size (ABCDE rule).</li>
    <li>A wound or cut doesn't start healing within a week.</li>
    <li>You experience recurring skin problems like eczema, psoriasis, or acne.</li>
    <li>Hair loss occurs suddenly or in patches.</li>
    <li>Nails become thickened, discolored, or brittle.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to See a Dermatologist</h2>
  <p>Your GP may refer you to a dermatologist (skin specialist) for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Persistent or severe skin conditions not responding to standard treatments.</li>
    <li>Suspicious skin growths or moles requiring further investigation.</li>
    <li>Chronic conditions such as psoriasis, rosacea, or hidradenitis suppurativa.</li>
    <li>Skin cancer screening or treatment.</li>
    <li>Specialized treatments like phototherapy, biologic medications, or surgery.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to Prepare for a Doctor's Visit</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Note your symptoms:</strong> When did they start? What makes them better or worse?</li>
    <li><strong>Medication list:</strong> All medications, creams, and supplements you use.</li>
    <li><strong>Medical history:</strong> Previous skin issues, allergies, and family history of skin conditions.</li>
    <li><strong>Photos:</strong> Take pictures of your skin at different stages — this helps assessment.</li>
    <li><strong>Questions:</strong> Write down your questions in advance so you don't forget.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Self-Care vs. Doctor's Visit</h2>
  <p>For mild skin issues like dry skin, mild eczema, dandruff, or athlete's foot, you can often start with over-the-counter products. See a doctor if self-care doesn't improve symptoms after 1-2 weeks. When in doubt, it's always wise to seek medical advice.</p>
</PageLayout>